# Git Cognition Protocol

*How to use Git without fighting it.*

-----

## The Core Translation

Git is a memory system. It does one thing: it remembers every state the repository has ever been in, and lets you move between them.

That’s it. Everything else is detail.

If you understand Git as memory, the commands stop being arbitrary and start being obvious.

-----

## The Mental Model

Think of your repo as a living document that exists in time.

- **The working directory** is what you can see right now — the current state of all your files.
- **A commit** is a snapshot — a complete record of every file at a specific moment.
- **The commit history** is the full timeline of every snapshot you’ve ever taken.

You are always working in the present. Git stores the past. You decide when to take a snapshot.

-----

## The Four Moves You Actually Need

### 1. Check what’s changed

```bash
git status
```

Shows you what files have been modified since your last snapshot. Run this before anything else. It orients you.

### 2. Stage what you want to save

```bash
git add .
```

The `.` means “everything that changed.” If you only want specific files:

```bash
git add filename.md
```

Staging is you telling Git: *I want to include this in my next snapshot.*

### 3. Take the snapshot

```bash
git commit -m "what you did in plain language"
```

The message is for future you. Write it like a note to yourself.
Examples:

- `"Added CPT gate instrument"`
- `"Moved fs-vocabulary into 01_stabilized_signals"`
- `"Fixed broken link in index"`

### 4. Send it to GitHub

```bash
git push
```

This syncs your local snapshots to GitHub. Until you push, your commits only exist on your computer.

-----

## The Full Sequence (Every Time)

```bash
git status          # what changed?
git add .           # stage everything
git commit -m "description of what I did"
git push            # send to GitHub
```

That’s the complete workflow. Four commands. You will use these every single time.

-----

## When You’re Starting Fresh (New Repo)

```bash
git init                          # start tracking this folder
git add .                         # stage everything
git commit -m "initial structure" # first snapshot
git remote add origin [URL]       # connect to GitHub
git push -u origin main           # send to GitHub for the first time
```

The `[URL]` comes from GitHub when you create a new repo. Copy it from there.

-----

## What Branch Means (Keep It Simple)

You are always on a branch. The default is called `main`.

For now: **stay on main.** Don’t worry about branches until the repo is stable and you have a collaborator who needs to work in parallel.

-----

## When Something Goes Wrong

**“I made a mistake in my last commit”**

```bash
git commit --amend -m "corrected message"
```

Only use this before you’ve pushed.

**“I want to see what a file looked like before I changed it”**

```bash
git diff filename.md
```

Shows what changed since your last commit.

**“I want to undo changes to a file I haven’t committed yet”**

```bash
git checkout -- filename.md
```

Warning: this permanently discards your changes to that file.

**“I’m confused about what state I’m in”**

```bash
git status
git log --oneline
```

`git log --oneline` shows your recent commit history in plain form. It tells you where you are.

-----

## The Cognitive Translation Table

|Git term         |What it actually means                              |
|-----------------|----------------------------------------------------|
|Repository (repo)|The folder Git is tracking                          |
|Commit           |A snapshot of the current state                     |
|Stage / add      |Selecting what goes into the next snapshot          |
|Push             |Sending your snapshots to GitHub                    |
|Pull             |Getting someone else’s snapshots from GitHub        |
|Branch           |A parallel timeline (don’t worry about this yet)    |
|Merge            |Combining two timelines (don’t worry about this yet)|
|Clone            |Downloading a full repo to your computer            |
|Origin           |The name for your GitHub remote                     |
|Main             |The name of your primary timeline                   |

